<br>
The RTA consists of guild representatives.  All the guilds on the server are, in theory, a part of it.  Whether a particular guild actively participates and is represented is their responsibility.  Someone can only be removed from a rotation or such by the request of the guilds participating in that particular rotation.  Guilds who were once, and could still, participate in a particular rotation are also given their say (for example, BotS no longer participates in the Yelinak or PoF rotations and it is clear that we still could if we wanted and we still have a voice)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> So if it's correct that the guilds who get there first make up the rules so that they can play nice with each other while the rest of us build up our guilds to even get to their level, don't you think that they should submit their agreements to the community? Don't you think all players should be able to reference these agreements as opposed to players from 20 guilds sending Karadin, Kenshiiro, Brotor or the Pope a /tell asking them to explain the agreements of the mobs in HoT while they are pulling AoW?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Before now, there weren't a lot of guilds pushing into the mid-level or high-level content.  Most everyone knew everyone else and what mobs were on rotation.  The guilds who were, knew who to talk to about rotation issues and it was easy.  Since a number of new guilds are pushing into these areas, it is probably best that the agreements be published for viewing (not review).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Then this agreement issue gets me thinking ...what if BoTS tells TL here's the agreement on AoW--You can't kill him unless you pay us 100k each time you kill the giant with the purple hat and if you don't pay us then you can't be on the rotation. Is NB, FK, LOL and LOM going to have to pay BoTS, too when they break the rotation?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, if such a thing were to happen, I'm sure Tindi would tell us that we are FoS and then we'd begin to hammer our a rotation agreement that all parties could agree upon.  Eventually, someone else WILL kill the mob and will also have their say.  Even if Tindi did agree to such a stupid agreement, BotS would have to give way or risk being pushed out of the rotation by the other two members.<br>
<br>
Many rotations lately were handled between BotS/Tindi/NB/(SoT) as simply stating that you killed MobX and wanted the 'standard rotation agreement' on it.  We all knew what this meant and would agree or hammer out a few details (like Ikatair/Eashen or named in HoT) in addition to that.  Agreements like ToVN didn't come about in a single day.  BotS and SoT representatives exchanged quite a few emails and even met in the game and in IRC to discuss the agreement.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> So I ask you, why doesn't the community as a whole get representatives to review these made up policies? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why would a guild of perpetual level 14 roleplayers need to have a say in content that they have not witnessed and probably will never participate in?  They would have some notion of fairness but they would have no clue as to the actual content involved.  Why would killing Aaryonyar give you 48 hour access to 8+ other mobs uncontested?  That doesn't sound too fair to all the other guilds.  What if other guilds wanted to kill one of those mobs other than Aaryonyar? Why can't they? Why do you need 48 hours? It's the mechanics of the game and encounters that make that agreement fair to the guilds involved.  At best, such voices would contribute to fairness, but if a guild is not pushing for fairness for itself, there is something wrong.  At worst (and far more common), such voices would add lots of noise and detract from the actual negotiation process.<br>
<br>
If you want a say in a rotation, fulfill the terms to get into the rotation and then you'll have a voice.  By that time, you will have experienced the content and will have a better insight into what it's all about.  Neither NB nor Tindi have never asked for a change in the ToVN rotation agreement.  Once they experienced it, I assume they saw that the agreement was reasonable and fair and found it agreeable to let it stand as it was.<br>
